Let me trace through the code very carefully for a URL that is just a single fragment like `#a` (exactly one char after `#`):

Original: `#a` → `replace(/#.*$/, '')` → `''` (empty string)
Mutated: `#a` → `replace(/#.$/, '')` → `''` (empty string) - same!

What about `#` alone (zero chars after `#`):
Original: `#` → `replace(/#.*$/, '')` → `''`
Mutated: `#` → `replace(/#.$/, '')` → `#` (no match, stays as `#`)

Then with baseUrlStr, `#` gets resolved... `URL.resolve('http://example.com/page', '#')` - this might produce `http://example.com/page#` which after `delete parsedUrl.hash` becomes `http://example.com/page`.

Without baseUrlStr, `#` goes through the protocol-adding logic and becomes `http://#` which `URL.parse` would parse with host as empty/null...

Let me test `#` without baseUrlStr:

```typescript
